   abstract = {The Mongol-Okhotsk Belt is a major structural element of East Asia. However, a number of important aspects of its evolution remain unresolved, in particular, the timing and scenarios of accretion and collision. This paper presents first detrital zircon U-Pb-Hf and whole-rock Nd isotope data from metasedimentary rocks of the Selemdzha and Tokur terranes in the eastern Mongol-Okhotsk Belt. Our new data suggest that these terranes are not part of a single sedimentary sequence, as has been previously assumed, but likely form a set of thrust sheets. The eastern Mongol-Okhotsk Belt hosts at least two types of accretionary complexes. The first type includes the Talyma, Zlatoust, Sagur-1, Tokur, and Ekimchan formations, which contain abundant Paleoproterozoic and Archean zircons, as well as Paleozoic zircons with two-stage model ages (t(Hf(C))) of 1.7 Ga. These formations are interpreted as fragments of a Paleozoic accretionary complex emplaced at the southern edge of the Siberian Craton. The second type includes the Afanas'ev and Sagur-2 formations, which lack Paleoproterozoic and Archean zircons but contain early Mesozoic zircons with t(Hf(C)) ages of < 1.4 Ga. The Afanas'ev and Sagur-2 formations are probably fragments of an early Mesozoic accretionary complex formed at the northern edge of the Amur Block. Our new model focuses on stratigraphic architecture of the Selemdzha and Tokur terranes and implies that two subduction zones of opposite polarities existed during the suturing of the Mongol-Okhotsk Ocean.},
